yt_title: Lady Gaga, Bradley Cooper - Shallow (from A Star Is Born) (Official Music Video) - YouTube
comment: This was definitely "A Star is Born" for the new generation.  Apparently, a generation that won't get it unless it's blasted in their face,  requiring actors to act without any  nuance, subtley or creativity.   As a result the masses loved it.   But unfortunately to the experienced , mature, educated movie goer it was really bad.   The whole movie was too cliche, heavy handed, over the top and try hard.  The line between brilliant acting and bad is so thin.  It requires a director to pull back actors at certain times, leaving creative room for the audience to respond.   None of that happened in this movie.   This movie really suffered from the vanity of an actor/director trying to do all and be all and yet there are several actors out there who would have nailed this role.   Instead of finding an actor with a the right voice, Bradley attempts to change his and it came off as exactly that.  Instead of finding an actor who could play the guitar, he has to learn how to play it himself and comes off as exactly that.  After you go through what he went through to "become" this role and then he's ALSO the director?   After all that work and sacrifice, if that same guy is the director, human nature prevents the best choices in how to depict it on film.   As a result it was "look how fantastic Bradley is" in every scene.   Meanwhile the character himself isn't all that fantastic.  The audience won't believe you and for those who view film with a nuanced eye, they didn't.     Bradley should have owned his role as a star or as a director but since the role was so far and away of who Bradley really is, it just didn't work.   It came off a try-hard vanity project.   One Star.    PS - even rock stars wash their hair every now and then and what was with the "sun burndt" look througout the entire movie?   It was just cute boy Bradley Cooper trying hard to look like the rough, gruff rock star/alcoholic.   People tended to compare Bradley with Meryl Streep in this role saying he "Meryled" it.  First of all if someone says you "Meryled" it and is comparing you to someone else, you didn't really do what they say you did.  Rather, you looked like you tried really hard at it.  When Streep does a role there is no sense that she's trying hard to do it, that's the unspeakable quality she has.  She just does it and it comes off without any effort, totally natural - a rare gift for any actor and she's directed by people who know how to show it, rather than focusing on it, resulting in an amazing, believable film.

comment: I am not a Bradley Copper or Lady GaGa fan but I wanted to see what all the hype was about. I am a Led Zeppelin, Al Pacino type of guy but went to go see this movie and while trying to fight back the tears I began wondering why I was so sensitive to this film and  realized Its about all of us. The beauty of beginning to fall in love,  Being in love,  That love begin to be threatened for whatever reason and suddenly things begin and cracks appear and our feet begin hitting the ground again ( love )  We yearn to feel it again and reminisce what we once had and we want the 2 hearts that beat as one to be whole again to the time we lifted each other up and completed one another.  These are some of the many thoughts I felt while watching this. It is the story of all our lives,  Being  a star in the one you love's eyes is much more powerful than being a star through Millions of eyes. If the one you love and cherish and the one that makes you feel complete begins to slip and fall you feel as if everything has come unglued.   My apologies for babbling but these are the many thoughts and emotions I felt watching this movie and then thinking about my own experiences with falling in love.  It was so real life this movie and yes,  I cried and more than once and you know what? For some strange reason I feel as If some untapped love and untapped hurt poured out of me from my experiences in life and if my tears from this movie were transferred to film, I would see the moments that conjured those feelings from my own life that brought me to tears. This movie was real life,  Now, Me being single and alone makes all of the feeling I felt from this movie more beautiful even if they hurt and even if I had to re live some of my life all over again LOVE was all worth it.   - Paul in Massachusetts
